quizzes.question:
What output results from the following code?
function test($num) {
    echo $num/2;
}
test(14);

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Function Parameters[/h1]

Information can be passed to functions through [b]arguments[/b], which are like variables.
Arguments are specified after the function name, and within the parentheses.
Here, our function takes a number, multiplies it by two, and prints the result: [code format="php" codeId="489"]function multiplyByTwo($number) {
  $answer = $number * 2;
  echo $answer;
}
multiplyByTwo(3);
//Outputs 6[/code]
You can add as many arguments as you want, as long as they are separated with [b]commas[/b].[code format="php" codeId="490"]function multiply($num1, $num2) {
  echo $num1 * $num2;
}
multiply(3, 6);
//Outputs 18[/code]
[note]When you define a function, the variables that represent the values that will be passed to it for processing are called [b]parameters[/b]. However, when you use a function, the value you pass to it is called an [b]argument[/b].[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to define the function "myMul", which takes two parameters and prints the product of their multiplication.
[!raw!]
function myMul($num1,{0}num2)  {
	echo $num1 {1} $num2;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Default Arguments[/h1]

Default arguments can be defined for the function arguments.
In the example below, we're calling the function [b]setCounter()[/b]. There are no arguments, so it will take on the default values that have been defined.[code format="php" codeId="491"]function setCounter($num=10) {
   echo "Counter is ".$num;
}
setCounter(42);  //Counter is 42
setCounter();  //Counter is 10[/code]
[note]When using default arguments, any defaults should be on the right side of any non-default arguments; otherwise, things will not work as expected.[/note]
